			<h4><a rel="nofollow" id="comment_link_65334265" name="comment_link_65334265" href="//linux.slashdot.org/comments.pl?sid=23676497&amp;cid=65334265" onclick="return D2.setFocusComment(65334265)" >Re:</a>


		 	<span id="comment_score_65334265" class="score"> (<a href="#" onclick="getModalPrefs('modcommentlog', 'Moderation Comment Log', 65334265); return false"><span class=opt>Score:</span>2</a>)</span></h4>
		</div>
		<div class="details">
			<span class="by"><span class="byby">by </span><a rel="nofollow" href="//slashdot.org/~Sique">Sique</a>  <span class="uid"><a rel="nofollow" href="//slashdot.org/~Sique">( 173459 )</a></span></a></span><span class="writes" style="display:none"> writes:</span> 
			<span class="otherdetails" id="comment_otherdetails_65334265"></span>
		</div>
	</div>
	<div class="commentBody">
		<div id="comment_body_65334265">The issue is that different languages have different rules for "case insensivity". In French for instance, the accent disappears when converting a lower case letter into an upper case letter. In Slavic languages, it does not. In German until recently, converting the Eszet to upper case required two letters, as the upper case version of &#223; was SS. But then the upper case &#223; was introduced, which made previous rules obsolete, and code had to behave differently.
<p>
Treating upper case and lower case lett<span class="substr"> </span></p></div>
	</div>

	<div class="commentSub" id="comment_sub_65334265">

</div>
