		<div class="details">
			<span class="by"><span class="byby">by </span><a rel="nofollow" href="//slashdot.org/~devslash0">devslash0</a>  <span class="uid"><a rel="nofollow" href="//slashdot.org/~devslash0">( 4203435 )</a></span></a></span><span class="writes" style="display:none"> writes:</span> 
			<span class="otherdetails" id="comment_otherdetails_65334313"></span>
		</div>
	</div>
	<div class="commentBody">
		<div id="comment_body_65334313"><p>On the fundamental level, a file name is just a string of bytes. Some of those bytes have equivalent glyphs (i.e. A, B, C, etc...) so that users can visually refer to those bytes and make sense of them in a natural way they understand. If we simplify to ASCII and ignore unicode, glyph 'A' represents byte 0x41 and glyph 'a' represents byte 0x61. These are two separate values so they need two different glyphs, two different identifiers which makes perfect sense. But what kind of a sick mind would you need to<span class="substr"> </span></p></div>
	</div>

	<div class="commentSub" id="comment_sub_65334313">

